	note = {Series Title: Coral Reefs of the World},
	pages = {3--27},
	annote = {although a pattern is beginning to emerge that connectivity tends to be higher for mobile species and perhaps less so for sessile species. These trends have important implications for questions about whether populations inhabiting MCEs can serve as refugia for corresponding shallow reef populations (Baker et al. 2016; Bongaerts and Smith 2019; Shlesinger and Loya 2019; Sponaugle and Cowen 2019). Although these are interesting observations, so little research has been done on connectivity in general that these patterns and trends should be viewed as preliminary.
},
	annote = {Similarly, algae play a key role in MCE communities, and while a fair bit of research has been published for MCE algae, much of this has been focused on biodiversity in a few geographic regions (particularly the Caribbean Sea and Hawaiian Archipelago; see Spalding et al. 2019a). Sponges (Porifera) are another dominant habitat-forming organism on MCEs (Pomponi et al. 2019). In addition to the large and conspicuous sponges, the diversity of more cryptic, encrusting sponges appears to be very significant on MCEs. The taxonomy of this group is in dire need of additional research in general, which compounds the need for further research on MCE sponges (Pomponi et al. 2019). Foraminifera are another group for which some information is known with respect to MCE communities, but much more is needed (Renema 2019).
Perhaps the most significant taxonomic gap for MCE biodiversity characterizations are the numerous other invertebrate phyla, many of which are extremely diverse among shallow coral reefs, and the same is likely to hold for MCEs as well. In particular, ascidians, crustaceans, mollusks, echinoderms, bryozoans, zoanthids, benthic ctenophores, and various other invertebrate groups appear to be well-represented on MCEs, but little has been done in terms of scientifically documenting these organisms on MCEs. Research has been published for some representatives of these groups (as cited earlier), but mostly in the form of new species descriptions. Yet, the role these organisms play on overall MCE biodiversity is far larger than what the historical publication record reflects.
