n particular, the Pocilloporidae, though preferring shallow depths, was found to be predominant also on the deep tiles. Tis family provides evidence of larval fow from shallow to mesophotic depths. For example, Stylophora had more juveniles in the mesophotic environment (×12) than would be expected based on its abundance in the adult population (Fig. 4c,d). Additionally, Seriatopora was not present in the adult communities at 50m, despite having been found on the settlement tiles at this depth. It is likely that these juveniles’ common origin is from a local larval pool, since these are brooding species, known for recruiting in their local habitat25. Hence, our study’s fndings may indicate that shallow reefs in the GoE/A may be considered as a local larval supply pool for the upper mesophotic reefs.
